Report: act_report¶

This report is the summary of Data analysis of the WeRateDog Twitter data archive. It discusses the visualization and insights produced from the data wrangling processes.

Data visualization and insightful analysis is the sorta fun part of data analysis. After long hours with data gathering, assessing and cleaning, all these are put together and make meaningful by the visualizations and insights drawn. See my wrangle_act files for detailed journey through the data wrangling processes, quality issues, tidiness issues and how they were fixed.

In this Udacity project visualizations, packages and functions where used to answer insightful questions about the dataset. Having stored the dataset as twitter_archive_master.csv, the following steps details my visualization processes.

First, as a rule of thumb, i imported the neccessay packages for this visualizations. knowing that i'll be making plots, matplotlib, seaborn and the ever present pandas were imported.

In [5]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

This displays the whole columns with integer as datatype. zeroing in on the columns: img_num still ranges form 1 (minimum) to 4 (maximum), maybe cause as at when data was gathered, maximum image per post was 4. retweet_count and favorite_count: now this's interesting. the count row dispalces the total count of each column and the mean row displaced the average. it can be seen that based on this data, tweets are more likely to get a favorite than a retweet. Tweeps just perfer to hit the like button than the retweet button.

Moving on to our next idea.

Insight #2:¶

With the day column data wont it be interesting to find out which day of the week gets the most tweets from Tweeps? My guess is that it is, so let's find out.

  1. Which day has the most Tweet?

Monday? Interesting, Let's visualize this one a chart; say pie

Awesome. Monday followed very closely by Wednesdays are the days with the most tweets from Tweeps (Twitter users). Why Monday though?

Insight #3:¶

It's one thing to make a post and another to engage with other post or actaully use the app. Though Monday is the day with the most tweets, let's see the day with the most tweet engagements. This can be arrived at by adding retweet_count and favorite_count to the picture. Hmmm, let's see;

In [11]:
df_clean_drf=df_clean.groupby(["day"], as_index=False)["retweet_count", "favorite_count"].sum()
df_clean_drf.sort_values(by=["retweet_count"], ascending = False).head(7)
